The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Setup Kubernetes Cluster Using Kind

It is necessary to setup the kubernetes cluster using Kind in order to understand it better. We will then explore its features by interacting with it.

  • Features of kind
    • High availability of control-plane.
    • Multi-node clusters setup.
    • Mapping ports to the host machine
    • Export cluster logs
    • Configure Proxy via kind

Open New Terminal (Optional)

If current working directory is not /home/ubuntu/ workspace/course

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as /home/ubuntu/ workspace/course
cd course/

Demo:

  • First of all download the kind binary:
curl -Lo ./kind "https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/dl/v0.17.0/kind-$(uname)-amd64"
chmod +x ./kind
sudo mv ./kind /usr/local/bin/kind
  • Breaking down the kind config
    • kind: Cluster specifies that the resource we're creating is a cluster.
    • apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4 specifies the API version to be used for this configuration.
    • nodes specifies the nodes that make up your Kubernetes cluster.
    • The first node is a control-plane (master) node. Control plane nodes host the components that control the cluster, such as the API server, controller manager, and etcd.
    • extraMounts is used to mount host paths into the control plane node containers. In this case, the host's /dev directory is being mounted to the container's /dev. This could be used, for example, to allow the container to access devices on the host machine.
    • extraMounts is also used to mount the host's Docker socket into the container. This allows the container to access the host's Docker daemon, which is used to build and run containers.
    • The next two nodes are worker nodes. Worker nodes run the containers (workloads) that your applications consist of.
    • networking is used to configure the networking settings of the cluster.
    • disableDefaultCNI: true disables the default CNI (Container Network Interface) plugin that comes with kind. This allows you to use a different CNI plugin, such as Cilium.
kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4
nodes:
- role: control-plane
  extraMounts:
  - hostPath: /var/run/docker.sock
    containerPath: /var/run/docker.sock
  - hostPath: /dev
    containerPath: /dev
- role: worker
  extraMounts:
  - hostPath: /var/run/docker.sock
    containerPath: /var/run/docker.sock
  - hostPath: /dev
    containerPath: /dev
- role: worker
  extraMounts:
  - hostPath: /var/run/docker.sock
    containerPath: /var/run/docker.sock
  - hostPath: /dev
    containerPath: /dev
networking:
  disableDefaultCNI: true
  • Now, use the 'kind-config.yaml' file to create a multi-node cluster. Here, we are creating 1 master node and 2 worker nodes.
kind create cluster --config=kind-config.yaml

  • Next, install "cilium" for networking.
cilium install

  • Verify "cilium" is running successfully by checking it's status. The output of "cilium status" should be "OK".
cilium status

  • Kubectl: Try to list namespaces to validate kubectl is able to communicate with the cluster.
kubectl get ns
